------------------------

  Right now, the ml/ folder is the offline ML preparation/training area. It is separate from the running application.

  Its job is:

  Read historical database data
  Clean/aggregate it
  Train a model
  Save the trained model file

  Example:

  ml/aggregator.py -> prepares training data
  ml/train.py      -> trains model
  ml/pipeline.py   -> connects aggregator + trainer

  That part is not the live agent yet.

  The rest of the project is the runtime framework. Its job is to start components, connect them together, and keep long-running
  services alive.

  Think of the project in two worlds:

  1. Offline world: ML training
  2. Runtime world: live application / agents

  Offline ML World

  This happens manually or on a schedule:

  Postgres historical data
    -> ml/aggregator.py
    -> ml/train.py
    -> sales_model.pkl

  The output is the trained model file:

  ml/sales_model.pkl

  Runtime Agent World

  This is where the rest of the project matters:

  main.py
    -> context.py
    -> config.json
    -> components
    -> AgentSales

  The agent will eventually load the trained model and use it while the app is running.

  The future flow is:

  main.py starts the app
    -> Context reads config.json
    -> creates PostgresDB
    -> creates AgentSales
    -> injects PostgresDB into AgentSales
    -> AgentSales loads ml/sales_model.pkl
    -> AgentSales makes predictions
    -> AgentSales sends result to Kafka or another service

  So the use of the rest of the project is not training. It is running the trained intelligence inside the application.

  Why Agents?

  An agent is a long-running worker.

  AgentSales is supposed to become the live “sales brain”.

  Later it can do things like:

  Every 30 seconds:
    read recent panier data
    clean it into features
    load/use trained model
    predict something
    publish suggestion

  Example prediction:

  "This panier is likely to be confirmed"
  "Suggest option X"
  "This product combination is popular"
  "This enseigne may sell more tonight"

  Why Database Connections?

  Because the live app needs access to real services.

  For example:

  PostgresDB -> read panier/product/client data
  RedisDB    -> cache fast temporary info
  InfluxDB   -> store time-series metrics
  Kafka      -> send events to other services later

  The ML folder can connect to Postgres directly for training, but in the runtime app, database access should go through components like
  PostgresDB.

  Why Configurations?

  Because you do not want hardcoded values everywhere.

  Instead of writing this in every file:

  host = "localhost"
  port = 5432
  password = "postgres"

  You put it in config.json.

  Then the framework reads it and configures components automatically.

  So changing database credentials later means changing:

  config.json

  not every Python file.

  Why Dependencies?

  Dependencies mean: “this component needs that other component.”

  Example:

  "agent_sales": {
    "dbPostgres": "postgres"
  }

  This means:

  AgentSales needs PostgresDB.
  Give the postgres component to agent_sales under the name dbPostgres.

  So inside AgentSales, you can use:

  self.getDependency("dbPostgres", PostgresDB)

  That is dependency injection.

  The benefit: AgentSales does not create its own database connection. The framework gives it one.

  Final Picture

  ml/
    trains the model offline
    produces sales_model.pkl

  main.py + context.py + config.json + components/
    run the live app
    connect services
    inject dependencies
    keep agents alive

  agent/sales.py
    will eventually load sales_model.pkl
    use PostgresDB
    make predictions
    send results somewhere

  So yes: ml/ is currently separate.

  But later, the bridge is:

  ml/sales_model.pkl

  The ML side creates it.
  The agent side loads it and uses it.